            "content": "Trenchless Pipe Lining Costs: $100-$250 per linear foot depending on pipe diameter, number of bends, and amount of preparation required. Typical 60-foot residential lateral: $8,000-$13,000. Includes: complete camera inspection ($350-$450 value), hydro jetting to remove all debris ($450-$650), epoxy liner material and installation, curing process, robotic cutting of lateral connections, final camera verification, and restoration of access pits. Additional costs: difficult access may require $500-$1,200 for additional entry points, severely corroded pipes requiring extra cleaning add $300-$600, and 6-inch pipe (vs. standard 4-inch) adds 30-40% to material costs. Traditional Excavation/Replacement Costs: $75-$200 per linear foot for pipe replacement, plus restoration costs. Typical 60-foot lateral: $7,000-$12,000 for pipe work. Additional costs that are often underestimated: driveway removal and replacement $2,000-$4,000, landscape restoration $1,500-$5,000, irrigation system repairs $500-$1,500, tree removal if blocking access $1,500-$3,000, and deeper pipes (6+ feet) requiring shoring add 40-50%. Total project cost typically $12,000-$20,000 when all restoration included. Pipe Bursting Costs: $100-$200 per linear foot. Typical 60-foot lateral: $7,500-$13,000. Includes: excavation of entry/exit pits, pipe bursting equipment and operation, new HDPE pipe, connections at both ends, pressure testing, and pit restoration. Lower total cost than traditional excavation due to minimal restoration needs. Spot Repair Costs: $2,000-$5,000 for isolated 10-20 foot damaged sections. Cost-effective when damage is truly localized, but risky for older sewer lines where additional sections likely to fail soon."
