            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": "Home Value Impact: A functioning sewer system is a basic requirement for home habitability—it doesn't add value, but a failing sewer system dramatically reduces value. Home sales with known sewer problems: buyers typically demand repair before closing or deduct 150-200% of estimated repair costs from offers (to account for uncertainty and hassle). A documented, recently repaired/replaced sewer system provides peace of mind to buyers and can be a selling point in neighborhoods with older infrastructure. Appraisers note major system replacements as recent improvements reducing deferred maintenance concerns. Avoided Costs: Preventing catastrophic sewer failure avoids: sewage damage to flooring, drywall, and personal belongings ($5,000-$25,000), foundation damage from soil erosion around leaking pipes ($8,000-$30,000), health department citations and mandatory repairs for sewage contamination, dramatically higher emergency repair costs (40-60% premium for after-hours/weekend emergency service), and temporary housing costs if home becomes uninhabitable during emergency repairs. Quality of Life: Beyond financial returns, proper sewer function provides: elimination of recurring backup stress and emergency calls, confidence to use all plumbing fixtures without fear of backups, peace of mind when traveling or during holidays, ability to host guests without embarrassing sewer odors or problems, and increased home comfort and safety. Many homeowners tell us the peace of mind alone is worth the investment after years of recurring sewer problems."
